  "prompt": "As an individual, can I get a patent for my ideas?",
  "response": "Yes, as an individual, you can apply for a patent for your inventions or ideas, provided they meet certain criteria. To be patentable, your invention must typically be:\n\n1. **Novel**: The invention must be new and not previously disclosed or known to the public.\n2. **Non-obvious**: The invention must not be obvious to a person having ordinary skill in the relevant field.\n3. **Useful**: The invention must have some utility or practical application.\n\nIt's important to note that you can't patent an idea alone; you must have a specific, tangible invention or process that embodies your idea. Additionally, the requirements for obtaining a patent may vary depending on the country in which you are applying.\n\nIf you decide to pursue a patent, you may want to consider consulting a patent attorney or agent to help you navigate the application process, as it can be complex and requires specific legal knowledge.",
